        optionFeedback: [`<!--Answers:-->Migratory arthritis following a tick bite and a local skin reaction is typical of Lyme arthritis. The causative agent is Borrelia (although it is only detected in inflamed joints in a minority of cases). The histology may resemble rheumatoid arthritis in severe cases. A distinctive feature is an arteritis that can give rise to thickening of the arterial wall. `,`Group B streptococcus can cause acute osteomyelitis in neonates and, by extension to the joints, give rise to arthritis.`,`Tuberculous arthritis is an unusual complication of disseminated tuberculosis, and usually is a more indolent arthritis, with granulomatous inflammation.`,`Disseminated gonococcal infection can cause acute septic arthritis, most often in immunodeficient individuals, particularly those with deficiencies of complement components. The microscopic picture is one of suppuration with neutrophilic infiltrate.`,`<!--E.-->Arthritis is rare in syphilis.`],
